\begin_layout Standard
There are many things that are assumed in CQT, such as the absence of zero
 norm states for non-zero vectors, and the decomposition of complex amplitudes
 into a pair of ordinary real numbers.
 One also typically assumes the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional Hilbert space with an orthonormal basis, allowing us to write
 
\shape italic
pure
\shape default
 states in general as Hilbert space vectors with an Hermitian inner product:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\ket{\Psi} & = & \sum_{i=0}^{D-1}\alpha_{i}\ket{i}\,.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\in\mathComplex$
\end_inset

 are complex probability amplitudes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\VVec{\alpha}\in\mathComplex^{D}$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ket{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis of states obeying 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{i}{k}=\delta_{ik}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The meaning of this is that any state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi}=\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}\beta_{i}\ket{i}$
\end_inset

