\begin_layout Standard
Entanglement may be regarded as one of the main characteristics distinguishing
 quantum from classical mechanics.
 Entanglement involves quantum correlations such that the measurement outcomes
 in one subsystem are related to the measurement outcomes in another one.
 Within the standard framework, given a quantum system composed of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 qubit subsystems, a pure state of the total system 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is said to be entangled if it cannot be written as a product of states
 of each subsystem.
 That is, a state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is entangled if 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}\ne\ket{\psi_{1}}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{\psi_{j}}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{\psi_{n}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 refers to an arbitrary state of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th qubit, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\otimes$
\end_inset

 represents the tensor product.
 This is equivalent to saying that if one calculates the reduced density
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th subsystem by tracing out all the other subsystems, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}=\Tr_{\{1,\cdots,j-1,j+1,\cdots,n\}}\left(\rho\right)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\cdots,n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\op{\Psi}{\Psi}$
\end_inset

, the normalized state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is entangled if and only if at least one subsystem state is 
\shape italic
mixed
\shape default
; i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\Tr_{j}\left(\rho_{j}^{2}\right)<1$
\end_inset

.
 For example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{j}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\sigma_{0}+\sum\limits _{\mu=x,y,z}\expval{\sigma_{\mu}^{j}}\sigma_{\mu}^{j}\right)\,,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mu}^{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=x,y,z$
\end_inset

, are the Pauli operators acting on the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th spin
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "544199"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\mu}^{j}=\overbrace{\sigma_{0}\otimes\cdots\otimes\sigma_{0}\otimes\underbrace{\sigma_{\mu}}_{j^{\textrm{th}}\textrm{ factors}}\otimes\sigma_{0}\otimes\cdots\otimes\sigma_{0}}^{n\textrm{ factors}}\,,\label{pauli3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{0} & =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\,, & \sigma_{x} & =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right)\,, & \sigma_{y} & =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -\rmi\\
\rmi & 0
\end{array}\right)\,, & \sigma_{z} & =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)\,,
\end{align}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\expval{\sigma_{\mu}^{j}}=\melem{\Psi}{\sigma_{\mu}^{j}}{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 denotes the corresponding expectation value.
 The vectors 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\bf X}_{j}=\left(\expval{\sigma_{x}^{j}},\expval{\sigma_{y}^{j}},\expval{\sigma_{y}^{j}}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

allow a geometric representation of each reduced state in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\left\Vert {\bf X}_{j}\right\Vert \le1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Tr_{j}\left(\rho_{j}^{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(1+\left\Vert {\bf X}_{j}\right\Vert ^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is entangled if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert {\bf X}_{j}\right\Vert <1$
\end_inset

 for at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, represented by a point 
\emph on
inside
\emph default
 the corresponding local Bloch sphere.
 One may therefore consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 to be maximally entangled if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert {\bf X}_{j}\right\Vert =0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is unentangled (i.e., a product state) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert {\bf X}_{j}\right\Vert =1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, corresponding to points lying on the surface of the Bloch sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A natural geometric measure of multipartite entanglement is obtained by
 defining the 
\emph on
purity of a state relative to a set of observables
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BKOV2003,BKOSV2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 If the set is chosen to be the set of 
\emph on
all local observables
\emph default
, i.e., corresponding to each of the subsystems that compose the actual system,
 one recovers the standard notion of entanglement for multipartite systems.
 For example, if the system consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 qubits, we obtain a measure of conventional entanglement by calculating
 the purity relative to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\fh=\left\{ \sigma_{x}^{1},\sigma_{y}^{1},\sigma_{z}^{1},\ldots,\sigma_{x}^{n},\sigma_{y}^{n},\sigma_{z}^{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{\fh} & =\frac{1}{n}\sum\limits _{j=1}^{n}\sum\limits _{\mu=x,y,z}\expval{\sigma_{\mu}^{j}}^{2}\,, & 0\leq P_{\fh}\leq1\,.\label{purityMeasure.eq}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\fh$
\end_inset

 is a semi-simple Lie algebra, its generalized unentangled states are the
 generalized coherent states obtained by applying any group operation to
 a reference state such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\overline{0}}=\ket{0}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{0}$
\end_inset

.
 For the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\fh$
\end_inset

 of local observables, such group operations are simply local rotations
 on each qubit.
 In other words, the group orbit describing the generalized coherent states
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\fh$
\end_inset

 comprises all the product states of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}=\ket{\psi_{1}}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{\psi_{n}}$
\end_inset

, which have maximum purity (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\fh}=1$
\end_inset

).
 Other states such as the Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}=\ket{\mathsf{GHZ}_{n}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\ket{0}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{0}+\ket{1}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 are (maximally) entangled relative to the set of local observables (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\fh}=0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different entanglement measures are obtained when a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\fh$
\end_inset

 different from the local observables is chosen.
 An obvious example, in particular, is given by the set of all observables.
 In this case, the purity takes its maximum value independently of the pure
 quantum state 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BKOV2003,BKOSV2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, expressing the fact that any state is a generalized coherent state of
 the Lie algebra of all observables.
\end_layout

