\begin_layout Standard
A field
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic structure consisting of a set of elements equipped with
 the operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fieldtheory.ref,numtheory.ref"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Fields may contain an infinite or a finite number of elements.
 The rational
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, real
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and complex numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 are examples of infinite fields, while the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}=\{0,1,2\}$
\end_inset

, under multiplication and addition modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, is an example of a finite field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two distinguished elements in a field, the addition identity 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, and the multiplication identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Given the field
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

, the closed operations of addition, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and multiplication, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\gmult$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 satisfy the following set of axioms: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

 is an Abelian group under the addition operation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 (additive group); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The multiplication operation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\gmult$
\end_inset

 is associative and commutative.
 The field has a multiplicative identity and the property that every nonzero
 element has a multiplicative inverse; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Distributive laws: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
a\gmult(b+c) & = & a\gmult b+a\gmult c\,,\\
(b+c)\gmult a & = & b\gmult a+c\gmult a\,.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


