 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for example).
 It turns out that if the characteristic is non-zero, it must be a prime
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 For every prime
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and positive integer
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 there is a finite field
\begin_inset space ~
