\begin_layout Subsection
Complexified Finite Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our next objective is to develop more realistic discrete quantum theory
 variants that exclude 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

supernatural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 algorithms such as the one presented above.
 Our first such plausible framework
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HOSW2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 is based on complexifiable finite fields.
 To incorporate complex numbers for quantum amplitudes, we exploit the fact
 that the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
irreducible
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1=0$
\end_inset

 has no solution) over a prime field 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 odd if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $4\ell+3$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 a non-negative integer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Artin1991,DummitFoote2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For example, given any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\ff{3}=\left\{ 0,\pm1\right\} $
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1=0^{2}+1=1$
\end_inset

; when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1=\left(\pm1\right)^{2}+1=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{3}$
\end_inset

.
 In contrast, over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{5}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{2}+1=0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 is reducible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We achieve our goal by observing that any field 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p=4\ell+3$
\end_inset

 is extensible to a field
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p^{2}}$
\end_inset

 whose elements can be viewed as discrete complex numbers with the real
 and imaginary parts in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p}$
\end_inset

.
 In a complexified finite field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fpp$
\end_inset

, the Frobenius automorphism that maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\Fpp$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p}\in\Fpp$
\end_inset

 acts like complex conjugation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Artin1991,grove2002classical,DummitFoote2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For example, in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fppx{3}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2+\rmi\right)^{3}=8+12\rmi-6-\rmi=2+11\rmi$
\end_inset

 which, in the field, is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2-\rmi$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $11\equiv-1\pmod{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the 
\emph on
field norm
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\fnorm{\cdot}$
\end_inset

