\begin_layout Subsection
Unentangled vs Entangled Discrete States
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a given 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding complexified field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fpp$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-qubit discrete quantum states with coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fpp$
\end_inset

 can be classified by their degree of entanglement to a level of precision
 that is unavailable in the continuous theory.
 We look first at the unentangled 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-qubit states, which are direct product states of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ket{\Psi}=\ket{\psi_{1}}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{\psi_{j}}\otimes\cdots\otimes\ket{\psi_{n}}\ .\label{dqcNqUntg.eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Without regard to normalization, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{4})^{n}$
\end_inset

 possible unentangled states out of the total of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2\times2^{n}}$
\end_inset

 states noted above.
 When we normalize the individual product states to unit norm, the norm
 of the entire 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-qubit state becomes the product of those unit norms, and is automatically
 normalized to one.
 We have already seen that each single-qubit normalized state in the tensor
 product 
