\backslash
Eq{
\end_layout

\end_inset

dqcNqUntg.eq
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $p(p-1)$
\end_inset

 irreducible components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Completely Unentangled States and the Discrete Bloch Sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In effect, the irreducible states for unentangled 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-qubit configurations reduce to a single Bloch sphere for each one-qubit
 component 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}$
\end_inset

, and thus the whole set of states is defined by an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuple of discrete Bloch sphere coordinates.
 Since each Bloch sphere in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fpp$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $p(p-1)$
\end_inset

 distinct irreducible components, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{{\bf Count of Unentangled States}}=p^{n}(p-1)^{n}\ .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We know that the total number of irreducible states (points in the generalized
 
\begin_inset Formula $\DCP{2^{n}-1}$
\end_inset

 Bloch sphere) for an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-qubit state is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2^{n}-1}(p^{2^{n}}-1)/(p+1)$
\end_inset

, and so the number of states containing some measure of entanglement is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{{\bf Count of Entangled States}}=\frac{p^{2^{n}-1}(p^{2^{n}}-1)}{p+1}-p^{n}(p-1)^{n}\ .
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore a very small fraction of the unit norm states are unentangled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Partial entanglement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A partially entangled state can be constructed by taking individual component
 states to enter as direct products, starting by picking 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

